    content: "# Restaurant GST Filing Guide 2026: Everything You Need to Know\n\nGST compliance is one of the most confusing aspects of running a restaurant in India. The rules are complex, the rates vary, and the penalties for non-compliance are steep. A restaurant in Delhi was fined Ōé╣2.4 lakh for incorrectly charging 5% GST when they should have charged 18% ŌĆö a mistake that could have been avoided with basic knowledge.\n\nThis guide covers everything you need to know about GST for restaurants in 2026.\n\n## GST Rates for Restaurants: 5% vs 18%\n\nThe most common source of confusion is which GST rate applies to your restaurant.\n\n| Restaurant Type | GST Rate | Input Tax Credit |\n|----------------|----------|------------------|\n| Restaurants NOT in hotels | 5% | ŌØī Not available |\n| Restaurants in hotels (room tariff < Ōé╣7,500/night) | 5% | ŌØī Not available |\n| Restaurants in hotels (room tariff Ōēź Ōé╣7,500/night) | 18% | Ō£ģ Available |\n| Outdoor catering | 5% | ŌØī Not available |\n| Takeaway / delivery | 5% | ŌØī Not available |\n| Alcohol (served in restaurant) | State VAT applies | N/A |\n\n**The simple rule:** If you're a standalone restaurant (not inside a 5-star hotel), you charge **5% GST** and cannot claim input tax credit.\n\n**Important:** The 5% rate applies to the total bill including food and non-alcoholic beverages. Alcohol is taxed separately under state VAT.\n\n## When to Register for GST\n\nGST registration is mandatory if your annual turnover exceeds **Ōé╣20 lakhs** (Ōé╣10 lakhs for special category states like Himachal Pradesh, Uttarakhand, etc.).\n\nEven if you're below the threshold, voluntary registration can be beneficial if you supply to other GST-registered businesses.\n\n**Documents needed for GST registration:**\n- PAN card of business/proprietor\n- Aadhaar card\n- Business registration certificate\n- Bank account details\n- Address proof of business premises\n- FSSAI license\n- Passport-size photograph\n\nRegistration is done online at gstin.gov.in and typically takes 3-7 working days.\n\n## GSTR-1: What It Is and When to File\n\nGSTR-1 is the outward supply return ŌĆö it reports all the sales you made during the period.\n\n**Filing frequency:**\n- **Monthly:** If your annual turnover exceeds Ōé╣5 crore\n- **Quarterly (QRMP scheme):** If your annual turnover is up to Ōé╣5 crore\n\n**Due dates:**\n- Monthly filers: 11th of the following month\n- Quarterly filers: 13th of the month following the quarter\n\n**What to report in GSTR-1:**\n- All B2B invoices (if you supply to other businesses)\n- B2C sales summary (for restaurant sales to individual customers)\n- Credit/debit notes\n- Advances received\n\nFor most restaurants, GSTR-1 is straightforward ŌĆö you're primarily reporting B2C sales.\n\n## GSTR-3B: The Monthly Summary Return\n\nGSTR-3B is a monthly summary return that every GST-registered business must file, regardless of turnover.\n\n**Due date:** 20th of the following month (for monthly filers)\n\n**What to report:**\n- Total outward supplies (your sales)\n- Total inward supplies (your purchases ŌĆö for ITC, if applicable)\n- Tax liability\n- Tax paid\n\n**Important:** GSTR-3B requires you to pay any GST liability by the due date. Late payment attracts interest at 18% per annum.\n\n## Input Tax Credit (ITC) for Restaurants\n\nHere's the painful truth: **most restaurants cannot claim Input Tax Credit**.\n\nIf you charge 5% GST (which most restaurants do), you cannot claim ITC on your purchases ŌĆö ingredients, equipment, packaging, etc. This is a significant cost.\n\n**The exception:** Restaurants in hotels with room tariff Ōēź Ōé╣7,500/night charge 18% GST and can claim ITC. For these restaurants, ITC can be substantial.\n\n**What this means practically:** If you buy Ōé╣1 lakh of ingredients and pay Ōé╣5,000 in GST on those purchases, you cannot offset that Ōé╣5,000 against your GST liability. It's a cost of doing business.\n\n## Common GST Mistakes Restaurants Make\n\n**Mistake 1: Charging wrong GST rate**\nCharging 18% when you should charge 5% (or vice versa) is the most common mistake. Always verify your applicable rate.\n\n**Mistake 2: Not including GST in menu prices**\nYour menu must clearly state whether prices are inclusive or exclusive of GST. \"All prices inclusive of 5% GST\" or \"Prices exclusive of GST\" ŌĆö be clear.\n\n**Mistake 3: Missing filing deadlines**\nLate filing attracts a penalty of Ōé╣50/day (Ōé╣20/day for nil returns), up to Ōé╣5,000. Set calendar reminders.\n\n**Mistake 4: Not maintaining proper records**\nGST law requires you to maintain records for 6 years. Keep all purchase invoices, sales records, and GST returns.\n\n**Mistake 5: Incorrect GSTIN on invoices**\nIf you issue invoices to other businesses, your GSTIN must be correct. An incorrect GSTIN means the buyer cannot claim ITC.\n\n**Mistake 6: Not reconciling GSTR-1 and GSTR-3B**\nYour GSTR-1 (sales reported) and GSTR-3B (tax paid) must match. Discrepancies trigger notices from the GST department.\n\n## FSSAI and GST Registration Requirements\n\nBefore you can register for GST, you need:\n- **FSSAI license:** Mandatory for all food businesses. Basic registration for turnover < Ōé╣12 lakh, State license for Ōé╣12 lakh - Ōé╣20 crore, Central license for > Ōé╣20 crore.\n- **Trade license:** From your local municipal corporation\n- **Fire NOC:** Required for restaurants above a certain size\n\nGST registration without FSSAI is possible but not recommended ŌĆö GST officers may ask for it during verification.\n\n## How Billing Software Auto-Calculates GST\n\nManual GST calculation is error-prone and time-consuming. Good billing software handles it automatically:\n\n- Applies the correct GST rate to each item\n- Separates GST from base price on the invoice\n- Generates GST-compliant invoices with your GSTIN\n- Produces monthly GST reports ready for filing\n- Calculates GSTR-1 and GSTR-3B data automatically\n\nBillByteKOT generates GST-compliant invoices automatically and produces monthly GST summary reports that make filing straightforward. Restaurant owners using BillByteKOT report spending 80% less time on GST compliance.\n\n**[Get GST-compliant billing from day one ŌĆö start your free 7-day trial ŌåÆ](/login?trial=7days)**"
